article.description: Kelly Miller scored 13 points and Tully Bevilaqua added 10 points and six assists as the Fever beat the Liberty 75-50 Saturday night.
article.headline: Fever tune up for playoffs with romp of Liberty
article.linkText: Fever tune up for playoffs with romp of Liberty
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indiana Fever hope Saturday night's
result was a sign of things to come.

Kelly Miller scored 13 points and Tully Bevilaqua added 10
points and six assists as the Fever beat the New York Liberty
75-50.

Indiana (21-13), which set a franchise record for victories, won
the season series 3-1 and will open the first round of the playoffs
at New York on Tuesday night.

"We've been pretty relaxed, and we wanted to come and feel good
going into the playoffs," Miller said.

It was the Fever's largest winning margin of the season and New
York's lowest scoring output of the year.

The Liberty (18-16) rested their starters for much of the game.
All-star Becky Hammon played just nine minutes and did not score.

"Our goal tonight was to play the players on the bench and not
get anybody hurt," New York coach Pat Coyle said.

New York's Crystal Robinson scored 12 of her game-high 19 points
in the first half, but the Fever led 35-30 at the break.

Fever forward Tamika Catchings, a candidate for the league's MVP
and defensive player of the year awards, finished with 11 points
and four rebounds in 26 minutes. She scored her final bucket on a
3-point play with 12 minutes remaining.

The Fever shot 51 percent from the field -- the third time in
five games they made more than half their shots-- including 8-for-18
on 3-pointers.

Five different Indiana players scored from 3-point range.

"We shot the ball well tonight," said Indiana coach Brian
Winters. "I think we had a pretty good flow going."

Winters expects a closer game on Tuesday.

"It's going to be a totally different game in New York," he
said. "They're a very good team, an experienced team with a lot of
playoff experience."

Robinson said the Liberty respect the Fever, and expect a
challenging best-of-three series.

"The Fever are a good team," she said. "We are a good team.
It should be an intense, good playoff series."
